UML:TaggedValue.value: Enterprise Architect XMI/UML 1.3

Examples include (www.casa.gov.au):
LOW INTENSITY: Low intensity obstacle lights are steady red lights and are to be used on non-extensive objects whose height above the surrounding ground is less than 45m.
MEDIUM INTENSITY: Medium intensity obstacle lights can be flashing red lights, steady red lights or flashing white lights. Medium intensity obstacle lights are to be used either alone or in combination with low intensity lights, where: (a) the object is an extensive one or (b) the object is 45m above the surrounding ground.
HIGH INTENSITY: High intensity obstacle lights are flashing white lights used on obstacles that are in excess of 150m in height. High intensity obstacle lights may also be used during the day, in lieu of obstacle markings, on obstacles that are in excess of 150m in height, or are difficult to be seen from the air because of their skeletal nature, such as towers with overhead wires and cables spanning across roads, valleys or waterways.
One or more light sources located on the ground and that provide visual assistance for air and ground navigation.

UML:TaggedValue.value:
the distance (in sea miles) in at which a light of a particular intensity can be seen in 'clear' visibility, taking no account of the earth curvature.
The range is related to the color of the light, e.g. WRG (white-red-green) the range 7-5 denotes 7 miles for white, 5 miles for green and red somewhere in between. Another example: WR (white-red) with range 23/22 denotes that white is visible in 23 miles, red in 22 miles.
